node.text:
Meet Mikhail Martin (@kaledoesit) — climber, software engineer and co-founder of Brothers of Climbing (@boccrew). Mikhail believes in challenging preconceptions about what exactly the ‘great outdoors’ is and creating opportunities for people to enter nature as they are.
 
“When you’re out in the outdoors, you’re just a little speck in there. It really gives us a broader perspective into where we are on this earth. And I feel like it humbles us. That humbling brings us back to why we should just appreciate the life that we have, and I feel like that’s something nature can do.” #OuterPeace #arcteryx

node.title: Mikhail Martin: Building a Community in Nature

How will you find it? #OuterPeace

This week, we’re celebrating three inspiring women, beyond their shells: a VP matriarch, an ER nurse moonlighting as a pro-skier, and an Olympian with an engineering degree. Almost as layered as our ski jackets.

node.text:
We believe the path to a better self begins in nature – outside of our doors and ourselves.⁣

Join us as we explore the transformative and healing power of nature and find our #OuterPeace.⁣
⁣
This year, we are committing $1 million to help support our partners in their work to remove the barriers people experience in accessing nature. Learn more about Outer Peace through the link in our bio.

node.text:
“Climbing in the big mountains is all about abiding by the age-old practices of patience, flexibility and spontaneous commitment when the time is right. No climb is a stand-alone endeavour. It takes a wide network of support, time spent listening and watching, plus a deep understanding and appreciation of history—and of the shoulders we stand upon—to reach for our dreams.” - @michaelogardner 

This spring, Mike Gardner and Sam Hennessey spent the season in Alaska. The duo wasted no time, adding a new line on Denali's Isis Face, Anubis (Alaska Grade 6: AI5, M6, 6,900'); ascending the classic Bibler-Klewin on the North Buttress of Begguya (Mt. Hunter); and then finishing it off by climbing Denali's Cassin Ridge. 

Link in bio to read more of Mike’s reflection on the @alpinistmag blog.

node.text:
From the well-protected "Peace" (5.13+) to the runout "Bachar-Yerian" (5.11 R/X), @cannonjtc appreciates the experience that each of these historic routes provide.

Although both routes represent a completely different ethic and mentality about climbing, Jordan believes that each style is valid and has a place in climbing.

"I don't want every route to be like the 'Bachar-Yerian,' but I don't want every route to be like 'Peace' either! I'm thankful for all of the subtle nuance and variety that there is in climbing. That's what keeps it exciting."

"Bachar-Yerian" (5.11 R/X) First Ascent: John Bachar and Dave Yerian, ground-up, 1981
"Peace" (5.13+) First Ascent: Ron Kauk, top-down, 1995

#GoClimbWeek
